article.headline: Silver Stars drop fourth in a row
article.linkText: Swoopes, Thompson lead Comets to 2nd straight win
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- The Houston Comets knew the San Antonio Silver
Stars were going to come back.

They did it before -- erasing a 13-point halftime deficit in
Houston on May 20 -- and it cost the Comets a win in their season
opener. This time, however, Houston was ready.

Sheryl Swoopes scored 20 points and Tina Thompson added 17,
leading the Comets to a 59-47 victory over the Silver Stars on
Wednesday night.

The pair combined for 24 in the first half and held off a late
San Antonio rally as the Comets avenged the earlier 64-55 loss.

"We were reminded at the half about what happened last time,"
Swoopes said. "We were not going to let that happen again."

Houston has won two straight following back-to-back losses to
Phoenix and New York last week.

Adrienne Goodson scored 15 points for the Silver Stars, who have
lost four in a row.

Marie Ferdinand, who scored 20 points against the Comets in the
second half of their first meeting, went 2-for-7 and scored nine
points.

"It's great to get a win tonight and I think we felt like we
owed them a little something from last time," Swoopes said. "In
the first half I thought we were as good as we've been all year,
especially defensively. That got us through the second half."

San Antonio got to within 46-41 with 6:10, but Thompson hit an
11-foot jumper and Kedra Holland-Corn sank a free throw to get the
lead back to eight for the Comets.

"We're too good of a team to keep getting ourselves into these
holes," Goodson said. "We came back, but at that point it's tough
to finish.

"It's unfortunate that we didn't come out on top tonight, but
we play them again on Saturday, so we've got to look forward to
that."

Houston closed out the game with a 6-0 run, shutting out San
Antonio in the final 1:50.

"They are a very competitive team, so we knew we were going to
have to play a 40-minute game," Thompson said. "They made a
little run in the second half which we knew was going to happen at
some point. We weathered the storm, but we came out with the
victory."

Houston used a 21-4 run in the middle of the first half to take
a 30-11 lead with 5:38 left. The Comets made four 3-pointers during
that stretch, including two each from Thompson and Swoopes, who
combined to make 10 of their 18 first-half shots.

^NOTES:@ Houston held San Antonio to a season-low 18 points in
the first half. The Comets shot a season-best 48.1 percent from the
field, making 25 shots on 52 attempts. ... Shannon Johnson had a
season-high four steals for San Antonio, which had 12 takeaways on
Wednesday. ... Houston's 12-point win was its largest margin of
victory in 2004. The previous high was 11 (68-57) at Connecticut on
May 25.
